&#xa0;
defaultWritten evidence from the Local Government Association (SRN 014)
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default1.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Local Government Association (LGA) is the national voice of local government. 
defaultWe work with councils to support, promote and improve local government.
default&#xa0;
default1.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWe are a politically-led, cross party organisation which works on behalf of councils to ensure local 
defaultgovernment has a strong, credible voice with national government.  We aim to influence and set the political agenda on the issues that matter to councils so they are able to deliver local solutions to national problems.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;
default2.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Strategic Roads Network 
default(SRN) 
defaultshould not be considered in isolation from the local roads network or from transport 
defaultprovision 
defaultas a whole.
default For instance, roads policy should be considered alongside, and integrated with, rail policy.
default 
defaultThis reflects an under
defaultlying principle running through the LGA’s  campaign, 
defaultRewiring Public Services
default, 
defaultwhich argues
default for
default a
default joined up
default approach to
default infrastructure investment
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultRoute based assessments need to be a genuine coproduction between local authorities and the Highways Agency
default and need to consider all modes of transport and the local road network
default. 
default&#xa0;
default2.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultInvestment in the SRN needs to be coordinated with the Strategic Economic Plans produced by 
defaultLocal Enterprise Partnerships (
defaultLEPs
default)
default,
default as well as existing City Deal agreements.
default&#xa0;
default2.4.
default&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulto avoid gridlock on our roads, including the SRN, 
defaultcouncils need greater influence over local transport provision
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.5.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Department for Transport’s (DfT)
default traffic estimates 
defaultdo not represent guaranteed futures which must be accommodated. 
defaultFuture traffic levels 
defaultdepend on the policies pursued today.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default6.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAction for Roads
default concerns itself chiefly with the 
defaultSRN. 
defaultH
defaultowever it recognises that ‘almost every journey starts or ends’ on the 98 per cent of the road network for which councils are responsible. 
default&#xa0;
default6.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe SRN cannot therefore be considered in isolation from the local roads network
default or 
defaultlocal transport as a whole
default (si
defaultnce
default traffic on the local network is influenced by the provision of alternative transpor
defaultt).
default&#xa0;
default6.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis is true in three ways in particular:
default&#xa0;
default6.3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe tendency of new roads to generate ‘induced traffic’ is a well-established fact and has led previous road building sch
defaultemes to fail to deliver anticipated benefits. Indeed as 
defaultAction for Roads
default points out 
default“
defaultroads support job creation and unlock new development
default”
default. This is good news when the traffic generated as a result can be accommodated (and when the developments are 
defaultgenuinely new rather than relocated)
default. However, 
defaultwhere the intention
default 
defaultbehind investment in the SRN is to encourage development, the ability of the local roads network to handle more traffic will have to be carefully considered as part of the investment plan. 
default&#xa0;
default6.3.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhere the aim of increasing SRN capacity is to relieve congestion investment needs to be 
defaultplanned in a manner that avoids creating
default substantial new traffic. Ignoring local transport provision while expanding the capacity of the SRN to meet a 46 per cent tr
defaultaffic increase by 2040 will simply move people more quickly between gridlocked local roads. 
default&#xa0;
default6.3.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMany of the current journeys on the SRN are relatively short-distance journeys which could be diverted from it by changes to local transport arrangements – either
default local road improvements or public transport alternatives. 
default&#xa0;
default6.4.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe tasks above cannot be performed by central government alone but will re
defaultquire effective coordination between 
defaultcentral and local government.
default&#xa0;
default6.5.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn practical
default terms we think three developments are required:
default&#xa0;
default6.5.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCouncils need to be
default equal partners
default in devising the route based strategies that will provide the basis of investment in the SRN
default&#xa0;
default6.5.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthe programme of investment in the SRN needs to be 
defaultcombined
default with investment in
default local major schemes via the Local Growth Fund and agreements reached through the City Deal process
default.
default&#xa0;
default6.5.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCouncils need to be able to manage traffic effectively both through direct traffic management means and indirectly via the provision of alternative means 
defaultof transport.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default7.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Government has spoken encouragingly of involving local authorities in devising the route based strategies which are intended to shape the 
defaultprogramme of investment in the SRN. These discussions are supposed
default to be completed in time to feed
default into
default a Roads Investment Strategy
default,
default to be published by 2015.
default&#xa0;
default7.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe route-based strategy approach offers an opportunity to make investment in roads more effective and is one the LGA supports. However, it remains to be seen how 
defaulteffectively the Highways Agency will engage with councils on this programme of work. 
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default8.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe development of the Roads Investment Strategy needs to be 
defaultcombined
default with transport investment through the LGF.
default&#xa0;default8.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAction for 
defaultRoads
default refers to the Government’s efforts:
default “
defaultto free up other money that local authoriti
defaultes use to fund larger projects…
defaultreduce the strings attached to local funding for major schemes
default”, and decentralise “
defaultdecision-making to reduce the number of situations where
default councils need to get approval from Whitehall before starting work
default”
default&#xa0;
default8.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultHowever
default,
default it is now clear that central control of spending has not been abolished and that
default,
default instead of the original DfT proposal to allocate money to Local Transport Boards, LEPs will now
default have to compete for funds through their Strategic Economic Plans. 
default&#xa0;
default8.4.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAt the time of writing it is unclear on what basis these plans will be judged, but it does seem that the timetable for their production means that work on them 
defaultneeds to be completed befor
defaulte anyone knows the order of priority in the roads programme. We believe that drafting a plan for transport in a LEP area with no knowledge of the timetable for i
defaultmproving the SRN in that area, 
defaultor even knowledge
default of what measures might be used, 
defaultadds to the co
defaultmplexity of the task and makes it more likely that the conclusions reached will be open to question. This problem is exacerbated 
defaultif an effective relationship has not developed between 
defaultthe Highways Agency 
defaultand the relevant LEP(s). 
default&#xa0;
default8.5.
default&#xa0; 
defaultOfficials at the Departme
defaultnt for Transport and the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills 
defaultare working hard with local authorities and LEPs to bring clarity to these pro
defaultcesses and address these issues. However, 
defaultwe struggle to see how it will be possible to sensibly align the
default roads programme and local transpo
defaultrt investment plans within the G
defaultovernment’s timetable. In any case
default,
default this process is not devolution. If the sums in the LGF were truly devolved
default,
default councils would be better placed to manage the uncertainty over the
default 
defaultRoads Inves
defaulttment Strategy
default because 
defaultthey would not have to commit themselves on other investment according to a centrally-
defaultdetermined political timetable (
defaultbased on the dates of general elections
default)
default.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default9.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIf these investment programmes are to deliver best value they need to be accompanied by effective traffic management at local level and the provision of alternative transport facilities
default,
default including encoura
defaultgement for cycling and walking. However, 
defaultcouncils cu
defaultrrently lack the tools to do 
defaultthis.
default 
