default&#xa0; 
defaultAction for Roads
default is right to recognise 
defaultthe “
defaultneed to give local authorities the freedom, the flexibility and the capacity
default”
default to 
default“
defaultshape the future of their local transport – especially the roles to be played by roads, by di
defaultfferent types of public transport and by cycling
default”
default. To date however
default,
default the current government has not lived up to its initial promises of devolution in transport.
default&#xa0;
default9.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultCouncils understand better than anyone that there is no bottomless pit of cash to solve ou
defaultr 
defaulttransport (or other) problems
default. If local transport networks are to b
defaulte improved we need
default to
default innovate, rather than simply
default spend more. If we are to get best value from transport investment
default,
default councils need to be positioned to consider local transport as a whole
default. This would allow them to 
defaultencourage the use of alternative modes where this is effective while increasing capacity to the local road network through intelligent interventions, both to accommodate increased traffic arriving from the SRN and to reduce the i
defaultmpact of local traffic on the SRN. If councils are to take the measures necessary to avoid gridlock in the next two decades they will need:
