defaulty. H
defaultowever
default,
default the prospect of pursuing a policy of 
default‘
defaultpredict 
defaultand provide
default’
default along the mid-range estimate of a 46 per cent increase in traffic on the SRN over the next 25 years
default (as suggested by the Government’s forecast)
default poses the question of  
defaultw
defaulthat will happen to this additional traffic when it leaves the SRN? 
default&#xa0;
default10.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Df
defaultT’s estimates suggest an increase in traffic outside the SRN of 
default23
default-64% leading to an increase in non-SRN congestion of 25-101%. However
default,
default the real picture will be much worse for councils than this suggests, as that congestion will be concentrated in particu
defaultlar areas, implying an increase in traffic in main urban centres which they 
defaultwould struggle to 
defaultaccommodate.
default&#xa0;
default10.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAction for Roads
default appears to gloss over this prospect by claiming that: “Strategic roads may be under more pressure than their local counterparts. 
defaultBetween 2000 and 2012, the last year for which there is confirmed data, motorists drove an extra ten billion miles on strategic roads, while traffic was steady on the rest of the network”.
default&#xa0;
default10.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis is 
defaultmisleading since 
defaultbetween 2000 and 2007 traffic 
defaultactually 
defaultgrew on both SRN and local networks
default. Since then, 
defaultSRN traffic levels have stabilised while traffic on the local roads network has fallen to 2000 levels. In other words when the economy was doing well local traffic was increasing and we suspect that pressure
default on local roads will increase by more than DfT predicts as the economy recovers.
default&#xa0;
default10.7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA 46 per cent increase in traffic is not inevitable. Nor is it desirable on an across the board basis. It is clear that road freight transport will be the essential carrier 
defaultof economic growth in the next quarter of a century and that the car will remain essential for many journeys, especially in rural areas. This makes it all the more important to provide alternative forms of transport where possible
default,
default so that the essential ca
defaultr and lorry journeys are not made impossible or inefficient by congestion. 
default&#xa0;
default10.8.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis reinforces the points we have made previously about the need for local authorities to be empowered to deliver better transport and free up the local road network.
